water.” Five British transports wrecked in the same gale; the David Porter sailed into Lateste six days later."},{"number":2,"category":"maritime","header":"A cargo that fought its way over","body":"A letter-of-marque was not quite a privateer: armed and commissioned, but carrying cargo to a destination — “force trade and fight their way or run.” He outran the brig Dotterall to Charleston bar, traded salt for cotton, and beat Wellington’s army to Bordeaux by weeks."},{"number":3,"category":"literature","header":"He wrote it all down at seventy","body":"Thirty years after the war the old captain assembled his logbooks and memories into book form — sixty years at sea, told with a lively pen. American Heritage was still printing his adventures in 1957."}],"slug":"george-coggeshall-1784"},"H00353":{"id":"H00353","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":5,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1761,"month":1,"day":4,"city":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1840,"city":"Litchfield","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00116","mother_id":"I00143"},"tags":["not_yet_fully_entered"],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 353"}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00355","children_ids":["H00825","H00826","H00827","H00828","H00829","H00830","H00831","H00832"],"marriage_number":1,"end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1815,"date_year":1782,"date_month":9,"date_day":28,"location_country":"United States"},{"spouse_id":"X00356","children_ids":["HD1277"],"marriage_number":2,"date_year":1817,"date_month":12,"date_day":16,"location_country":"United States"}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"cousin_marriage","related_id":"HD6319","display_label":"is the cousin whose son George married his daughter Sarah","li